04516nam a2200661Ia 9781782046202DE-B159720240426104009.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240426t20162016xxk    fo  d z      eng d  a97817820462027 a10.1515/97817820462022doi  a(DE-B1597)677155  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxkcUK 7aREL0440002bisacsh04a287.4/411 aCalder, Sandy, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Origins of Primitive Methodism /cSandy Calder. 1aWoodbridge, Suffolk : bBoydell and Brewer, c[2016] 4c©2016  a1 online resource (316 p.) :b10 b/w illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aStudies in Modern British Religious History ;v3300tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Illustrations -- tPreface -- tForeword -- tAcknowledgements -- tAbbreviations -- t1 Introduction -- t2 The Historiography Problem -- t3 The Sources Problem -- t4 The Bourne Problem -- t5 A Third-Party View of Early Primitive Methodism -- t6 The Baptismal Registers -- t7 The 1851 Religious Census -- t8 The PM Chapel -- t9 The Character of the Leadership -- t10 Conclusions and a Reinterpretation -- tAppendix A Attendance, Attenders and Membership Patterns -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe Primitive Methodist Connexion's mature social character may have been working-class, but this did not reflect its social origins.This book shows that while the Primitive Methodist Connexion's mature social character was working-class, this did not reflect its social origins. It was never the church of the working class, the great majority of whose churchgoers went elsewhere: rather it was the church whose commitment to its emotional witness was increasingly incompatible with middle-class pretensions. Sandy Calder shows that the Primitive Methodist Connexion was a religious movementled by a fairly prosperous elite of middle-class preachers and lay officials appealing to a respectable working-class constituency. This reality has been obscured by the movement's self-image as a persecuted community of humble Christians, an image crafted by Hugh Bourne, and accepted by later historians, whether Methodists with a denominational agenda to promote or scholars in search of working-class radicals. Primitive Methodists exaggerated their hardships and deliberately under-played their social status and financial success. Primitive Methodism in the later nineteenth and early twentieth centuries became the victim of its own founding mythology, because the legend of a community of persecuted outcasts, concealing its actual respectability, deterred potential recruits. SANDY CALDER graduated with a PhD in Religious Studies from the Open University and has previously worked in the private sector.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 4aHistory of Religion. 4aModern History. 7aRELIGION / Christianity / Methodist.2bisacsh  a1900s.  aChristianity.  aPrimitive Methodist Connexion.  aanthropology.  achurch.  amethodism.  amethodist church.  amiddle class.  areligion.  asocioeconomic status.  asociology.  atwentieth century.  aworking class.1 aWellings, Martin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311143131440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781782046202?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781782046202423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781782046202/original  a978-3-11-143131-4  Boydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aGBV-deGruyter-alles